Amazing. Because I’m currently thinking about designing a new trading system. And I’m approaching it from OOP (data, strategies, rules, portfolio theory, simulations, limits, “buy/sell indicators” etc) basically clean data -> processor -> execution. But what would a ROP or ECS implementation of a financial trading strategy look like



Applying ECS to a financial trading system is a phenomenal thought experiment, and in the world of High-Frequency Trading (HFT) or massive-scale backtesting, it is actually closer to how the most performant systems are built.

In your standard OOP approach, the system is a bucket brigade. An Asset object gets new data, passes it to a Strategy object, which evaluates it and passes an Order object to a RiskManager object, and so on. The state is fragmented across dozens of objects, and modifying the pipeline requires rewiring the objects.

In an ECS or ROP model, the system is a conveyer belt with specialized laser scanners. The data flows flat and fast, and the logic only triggers when the right combination of data passes by.

Here is how you would map a trading system into an Entity-Component-System architecture.

1. Entities (The "What")
In a trading ECS, an Entity is just a unique integer ID. It usually represents a specific tradable asset (e.g., ID 101 = AAPL, ID 102 = TSLA). It has absolutely no code, no methods, and no data attached to it directly.

2. Components (The "State")
Instead of objects holding their own state, all state is broken down into raw, flat arrays (or database tables) aligned by Entity ID.

MarketData Component: [current_price, bid, ask, volume]

MovingAverage Component: [short_window_val, long_window_val]

Position Component: [current_holdings, average_cost]

RiskProfile Component: [max_exposure, stop_loss_pct]

ProposedTrade Component: [action_type, quantity, confidence_score]

3. Systems (The "Relationships" and "Processors")
The magic happens in the Systems. Systems do not know what an "Apple stock" is. They only care about the relationships between specific arrays of data. They run sequentially in a massive loop (the "tick").

System A: The Indicator System
This system asks: "Give me every Entity ID that has both MarketData AND a MovingAverage component." It zips down the arrays, takes the new price from MarketData, updates the math in MovingAverage, and moves on.

System B: The Strategy System
This system asks: "Give me every Entity ID with MarketData AND MovingAverage."
It checks if the short-term average crossed the long-term average. If it did, it doesn't call a "buy" function. Instead, it simply attaches a new ProposedTrade component to that Entity ID (e.g., [Buy, 100 shares, High Confidence]).

System C: The Risk System (The ultimate relationship manager)
This is where ECS shines. In OOP, tightly coupling risk limits to strategy generation is a nightmare. Here, they are beautifully decoupled.
The Risk System asks: "Give me every Entity ID that has a ProposedTrade AND a RiskProfile AND a Position."
It looks at the proposed 100 shares. It checks the RiskProfile max exposure and the current Position. If buying 100 shares breaches the risk limit, the Risk System simply deletes or modifies the ProposedTrade component. It doesn't care what strategy generated the trade; it only enforces the relationship between intent and risk.

System D: The Execution System
This system asks: "Give me every Entity ID that currently has a ProposedTrade component."
Because the Risk System already scrubbed the bad trades, the Execution System blindly trusts what is left. It sends the API call to the broker, and then deletes the ProposedTrade component so it doesn't fire again on the next tick.

The Massive Advantages for Trading
Infinite Composability: Want to test a new RSI strategy alongside your Moving Average strategy? You don't rewrite your Asset class. You just create an RSI_Strategy component and an RSI_System to process it. If both systems attach a ProposedTrade to AAPL, the Execution system handles it flawlessly.

Blistering Speed for Backtesting: Because all your MarketData and Strategy math are in flat, contiguous C++ or Rust arrays, your CPU cache isn't jumping around memory looking for objects. You can backtest millions of ticks across thousands of assets in a fraction of the time OOP takes.

Perfect Separation of Concerns: Your strategy logic never touches your risk logic, and neither touches your execution logic. They only communicate by adding or removing pure data components on an entity.

It is a completely different way of mapping the financial world, shifting the focus from "smart objects" to "dumb data and smart pipelines."

Would you like to explore how you would handle complex, multi-asset relationships in this model (like pair trading or portfolio-wide rebalancing, where one entity depends on another), or dig into how you might structure the memory layout for this?


This is a fiercely well-thought-out PRD. You already have a distinct advantage here: your 4-phase architecture is already conceptually structured as a data pipeline rather than a web of tangled objects.

However, your stack.md mentions an Actor Model. The Actor Model is essentially the ultimate form of OOP—independent "objects" (actors) passing messages to each other. To truly embrace ECS and Relationship-Oriented Programming, we need to strip away the "actors" and replace them with flat data arrays (Components) and sequential logic loops (Systems).

Here is how your PRD looks when rewritten for an ECS architecture.

Product Requirements Document (PRD): The Neurosymbolic Quant Fund (ECS Architecture)
1. System Overview
This project builds a fully automated quantitative trading system designed for a 3-6 month holding horizon. Instead of relying on isolated strategy "objects" or an Actor Model, the system utilizes an Entity-Component-System (ECS) architecture to process market realities as flat, highly performant data streams. The system strictly avoids HFT, focusing on fundamental value, macroeconomic Arbitrage Pricing Theory (APT) factors, credit market divergences, and sentiment exhaustion.

2. Core Philosophy: Heuristics Over Black Boxes (Data Separated from Logic)
This system rejects pure End-to-End Deep Learning for trade generation. It uses a Neurosymbolic / ECS approach.

Entities are Dumb: A ticker (e.g., AAPL) is merely an integer ID. It has no behavior.

Rigid Heuristics (Systems): We use mathematically deterministic logic loops (Dynamic DCF, CDS spread divergence) to evaluate raw data components and generate "Score" components.

Machine Learning as a System: ML (XGBoost) acts purely as a downstream System that reads "Score" components to generate "Target Weight" components.

Tournament-Tested Components: All Systems must survive a Walk-Forward Optimization (WFO) tournament, ensuring the logic mutates data effectively before touching live capital.

3. The ECS Pipeline Architecture
Instead of passing data between "Desks," the system runs sequential Systems (logic loops) over flat Component arrays (data tables).

A. Entities (The Identifiers)

Entity ID: A unique integer representing a tradable asset.

B. Components (The State / Flat Data Arrays)

MarketData: [EOD_price, volume, options_IV, credit_spread]

FundamentalData: [cash_flow, debt, outstanding_shares]

TacticalScores: [Z_score, apt_expectation, npv_gap]

RegimeData: [macro_state, volatility_index]

RiskProfile: [short_interest, borrow_cost, liquidity_metric]

ActionIntent: [target_portfolio_weight, conviction_score]

ProposedOrder: [direction, quantity, limit_price]

C. Systems (The Logic Loops / Relationships)
The system ticks continuously through these sequential loops:

Ingestion System: Queries external APIs and purely overwrites the MarketData and FundamentalData component arrays for all active Entity IDs.

